## Quiz

?? Why does binary search require the array to be sorted?
>> The algorithm uses the comparison `arr[mid] < target` to decide which half to discard. That decision only works if elements to the left of `mid` are all ≤ `arr[mid]` and elements to the right are all ≥ — i.e. the array is sorted. On an unsorted array the elimination step could discard the target.

?? What is the time complexity of binary search on an array of size n, and why?
>> $O(\log n)$. Each comparison halves the remaining search window, so the window shrinks from $n$ to $n/2$ to $n/4$ … to 1 in at most $\lceil \log_2 n \rceil$ steps.
